<paper id="1967992696"><title>Efficient optimization of a class of relational expressions</title><year>1979</year><authors><author org="Bell Laboratories Murray Hill NJ" id="2380581373">A. V. Aho</author><author org="Princeton Univ., Princeton, NJ" id="2805146941">Y. Sagiv</author><author org="Princeton Univ., Princeton, NJ" id="2289364316">J. D. Ullman</author></authors><n_citation>181</n_citation><doc_type>Journal</doc_type><references><reference>36983325</reference><reference>43035074</reference><reference>173390059</reference><reference>1655990431</reference><reference>1975442866</reference><reference>1975714036</reference><reference>1979514837</reference><reference>1985581502</reference><reference>2011039300</reference><reference>2020601345</reference><reference>2032386524</reference><reference>2036265926</reference><reference>2038765730</reference><reference>2039187793</reference><reference>2071678949</reference><reference>2110810394</reference><reference>2125223317</reference><reference>2138709157</reference><reference>2165467455</reference><reference>2169012378</reference><reference>2232207765</reference></references><venue id="90119964" type="J">ACM Transactions on Database Systems</venue><doi>10.1145/320107.320112</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.64473">Query optimization</keyword><keyword weight="0.6779">Codd's theorem</keyword><keyword weight="0.6648">Relational calculus</keyword><keyword weight="0.70119">Conjunctive query</keyword><keyword weight="0.629">Relational database</keyword><keyword weight="0.45291">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.47055">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.64077">Relational algebra</keyword><keyword weight="0.63543">Relational model</keyword><keyword weight="0.59538">Domain relational calculus</keyword><keyword weight="0.42574">Database</keyword></keywords><publisher>ACM</publisher><abstract>The design of several database query languages has been influenced by Coddu0027s relational algebra. This paper discusses the difficulty of optimizing queries based on the relational algebra operations select, project, and join. A matrix, called a tableau, is proposed as a useful device for representing the value of a query, and optimization of queries is couched in terms of finding a minimal tableau equivalent to a given one. Functional dependencies can be used to imply additional equivalences among tableaux. Although the optimization problem is NP-complete, a polynomial time algorithm exists to optimize tableaux that correspond to an important subclass of queries.</abstract></paper>